%N A397216 a(n) is the number of distinct triples of triangles chosen from n^2 unit triangles of a triangular grid with their centers collinear up to rotation.
%C A397216 Oblique coordinate system is defined taking x axis and y axis along two edges of the triangular grid of unit triangles n^2. Side length of a unit triangle is taken as 3 units to obtain integer coordinates for the centroids of all unit triangles. Each triangle in the grid is uniquely denoted by coordinates of its centroid. The centroid of a triangle is referred as the center of that triangle.
%C A397216 Three centers (x_1,y_1),(x_2,y_2) and (x_3,y_3) are collinear if (y_1-y_2)*(x_2-x_3) = (x_1-x_2)*(y_2-y_3).
%H A397216 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="/A397216/b397216.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..100</a>
%H A397216 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A397216/a397216.txt">Python code for A397216</a>
%e A397216 n = 4 has the following distinct triples of triangles:
%e A397216  {(4,1), (7,1), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(1,10), (4,7), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(1,10), (7,4), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(4,4), (8,2), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(2,5), (8,2), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(4,7), (7,4), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(2,5), (4,4), (10,1)},
%e A397216  {(4,7), (5,5), (7,1)},
%e A397216  {(4,1), (4,4), (4,7)},
%e A397216  {(4,1), (5,2), (7,4)},
%e A397216  {(2,8), (5,5), (8,2)},
%e A397216  {(2,8), (4,4), (5,2)}.
%e A397216 Therefore a(4) = 12.
